<paragraph blockId="9.[167,778,1375,2091]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">
<emphasis box="[168,778,1754,1778]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="678" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,330,1754,1778]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Identification.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="mephitis" authorityName="mephitis (Schreber" authorityYear="1776" box="[340,537,1754,1778]" class="Mammalia" family="Mephitidae" genus="Mephitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="9" pageNumber="678" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mephitis">
<emphasis box="[340,537,1754,1778]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Mephitis mephitis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished
</emphasis>
from other skunks in the area by the conspicuous white stripe running dorsally from head to tail. The stripe begins as a single white hair spot on the head and divides into two thinner stripes (
<bibRefCitation author="Wade-Smith J &amp; Verts BJ" box="[436,745,1888,1913]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref11460" refString="Wade-Smith J, Verts BJ (1982) Mephitis mephitis. Mammalian Species 173: 1 - 7. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3503883" type="journal article" year="1982">Wade-Smith and Verts 1982</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="678" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[167,778,1375,2091]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,317,1927,1951]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[327,412,1927,1951]" name="Canada" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Canada</collectingCountry>
, most of the 
<collectingCountry box="[565,620,1928,1952]" name="United States of America" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">USA</collectingCountry>
, and northern 
<collectingCountry box="[168,250,1961,1985]" name="Mexico" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wade-Smith J &amp; Verts BJ" box="[262,569,1961,1985]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref11460" refString="Wade-Smith J, Verts BJ (1982) Mephitis mephitis. Mammalian Species 173: 1 - 7. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3503883" type="journal article" year="1982">Wade-Smith and Verts 1982</bibRefCitation>
). Recorded habitats in 
<collectingRegion box="[195,313,1994,2018]" country="Mexico" name="Chihuahua" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Chihuahua</collectingRegion>
are sierras, valleys and arid.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="678" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[167,778,1375,2091]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,279,2033,2057]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Remarks.</emphasis>
Striped Skunk is widely distributed in the state (
<bibRefCitation author="Lopez-Gonzalez C &amp; Garcia-Mendoza D" box="[236,721,2067,2091]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678" pagination="1122 - 1133" refId="ref10434" refString="Lopez-Gonzalez C, Garcia-Mendoza D (2012) A checklist of the mammals (Mammalia) of Chihuahua, Mexico. Check List 8 (6): 1122 - 1133. https: // doi. org / 10.15560 / 8.6.1122" type="journal article" year="2012">López-González and García-Mendoza 2012</bibRefCitation>
) and
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[810,1420,160,217]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">is absent only in quebradas where only Hooded Skunk occurs.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
